{
  "text": "We also examined the effect of disrupting the zinc finger on protein translation rate and turnover. Using in itro transcription and translation, we found that there was no effect on the translation rate of CK2β C\"!*,\"\"%S . However, studies using a protein synthesis inhibitor demonstrated that Mycβ C\"!*,\"\"%S was turned over much faster than Mycβ. We have previously shown that β-subunits are synthesized in excess of α-subunits using biosynthetic labelling experiments [CITATION_1] . Moreover, this study demonstrated that β subunits that are not incorporated into tetrameric CK2 complexes are quickly degraded. The results presented here are in good accordance with this study. Our results show that a zinc-finger mutant of CK2β that is not incorporated into dimeric or tetrameric complexes is quickly degraded.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "45047405"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "45047405": {
      "title": "Biosynthesis of casein kinase II in lymphoid cell lines",
      "abstract": "We have analyzed the biosynthesis of casein kinase II. In exponentially growing tissue culture cells, the beta subunit was synthesized in excess of the catalytic subunit (alpha). A substantial fraction of newly synthesized beta was degraded within the first hour. The remaining fraction of beta was incorporated into holoenzyme. In contrast, little degradation of newly synthesized alpha subunit was observed and most was quickly and efficiently incorporated into holoenzyme. The assembly of beta with alpha was paralleled by an increase in apparent molecular mass of beta due to phosphorylation. The subcellular distribution of newly synthesized [35S]Met-labelled casein kinase II and of enzyme labelled and chased in the presence of excess unlabelled methionine was very similar and compatible with a nuclear localization. The degradation of the excess beta subunit occurred through a non-lysosomal proteolytic system with a very low ATP requirement."
    }
  }
}